http://www.supplychaindataanalytics.com/proximity-based-spatial-customer-grouping-in-r/

Use K-means clustering, but first define starting points based on the longitude dimensions of the spatial dataset

# define a fct
initial_centers <- function(stations,centers){
  quantiles <- c()
  for(i in 1:centers){
    quantiles <- c(quantiles,i*as.integer(nrow(stations)/centers))
  }
  quantiles
}

cluster_obj <- kmeans(rock_cluster,centers=rock_cluster[initial_centers(rock_cluster,6),])

Spring vs. late summer

Seasonal changes was one question that Ali, Wes, and I discussed looking at with these data. So the question would be, how many samples fall into those categories by year?

What about treating April differently from June?

If we have ~1000 samples to genotype initially, there are a couple of things I would do: 1. look at composition over the longest time period available (April-August) 2. look at changes in composition across years using best available comparative data (May/June) 3. ignore spatial distribution (for now?)

Assume ~100 samples per Month/Year… how many samples in each category?

April 2013 (927) May 2011 (759) June 2011 (28) July 2012 (1277)* August 2012 (99)

May 2009 (26) June 2009 (7) June 2011 (28) May 2015 (1022) June 2015 (645)
